Wash and dry all produce. Bring a #medium pot{} of salted water to a boil. Halve, peel, and thinly slice the @red onion{1%. Finely chopped}(peeled and thinly sliced. Cut the corn kernels off the @corn on the cob{1}(kernels cut off the cob). Core, seed, and dice the @green bell pepper{1}(cored, seeded, and diced). Juice half the @lime{1%half juiced}; cut the other half into wedges. Finely chop the @garlic{2%cloves}(minced) and @cilantro{1/4%ounce}(finely chopped). Drain and rinse the @black beans{1%box}(drained and rinsed).

Add the @cheese tortellini{9%ounce} to the boiling water and cook for ~{5-7%minutes}, until tender and floating to the top of the water. Drain, then toss with a drizzle of @olive oil{} to prevent the tortellini from sticking.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add the onion and bell pepper and cook, tossing for ~{4-5%minutes}, until softened. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add the corn, garlic, and a pinch of @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} (to taste) to the pan and cook for ~{2-3%minutes}, until the corn is tender. Season with salt and pepper.

Add the beans, tortellini, @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, and lime juice to the pan and toss for ~{1-2%minutes}, until a creamy sauce has formed. Remove the pan from the heat and stir in half the cilantro.

Serve: Garnish the southwest tortellini salad with the remaining cilantro and @pepitas{1%ounce} on top. Serve lime wedges to the side for squeezing. Enjoy!

> Get ready for a Southwestern twist on pasta salad! This warm salad is full of beans,
> cilantro, corn, and chili flakes for a very unique spin. Cheese-filled tortellini
> are a major upgrade from regular old pasta.